title: Capresso Infinity Doser Tray Mod
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I use my Capresso Infinity burr grinder daily to grid beans for espresso.
With a bit of experimentation, I found that my portafilter fit directly in the area where the grounds hopper usually sits.

This was great and made me think "what if I 3d printed a mod to make the Infinity grinder into a doser.
So, this project was born.

I wanted to make a fitted bin to hold stray grounds that miss the portafilter and I wanted to make guide rails to help hold the portafilter similar to a real doser.

In the future after iterating on this design I hope to actually mod the electronics of the grinder to have a temporary switch to auto time and fill the portafilter (avoiding the awkward and inconsistent timer knob on the Infinity).

To build this, I used calipers to measure the existing coffee ground hopper.
This was fairly tricky since all of the sides of the ground hopper are sloped and have curved and rounded edges.
After measuring, I printed the 3d duplicate using Vase mode in Cura to ensure a proper fit of the footprint in Sketchup.

Next, I measured my portafilter and handle (this one is measured from a Mr Coffee ECMP1000, but it should work with smaller sized household portafilters.
From the portafilter measurements, I created the guide rails and used the extrude tool to create the "catch bin" under the portafilter.

I still am working on tuning this and building a cover tray to make things a bit more appealing rather than having a big open catch bin.

This is a small static Antique Well Hand Pump I designed to use as a Garden Fountain.

The pump is probably around 8" tall and it mounts to a piece of 1" (I.D.) piece of PVC pipe so you can make it as high or lower as you want.

I used Super glue to join the parts and the bottom flange is also glued to the PVC. The Pump handle mounts to the pump with a few 6-32" screws and I think the flange screws/nuts are 4-40.

I did very little post process sanding so I painted it with Rust-Oleum Universal Antique Pewter Hammered Enamel Spray Paint to cover up the layer lines.

I used this Water Pump (https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01KLBNCGG) and a piece of 5/16 id hose to connect it to the Fountain. I have it hooked to a battery/solar panel/controller so it only runs during the day for a few hours while the sun is out.

title: Printrbot LC part cooling fan mount

description.text: After doing a lot of reading and a bit of testing this fan mount was the best solution I have yet found for the Printrbot LC. I tried the http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:21462 fan mount, but it acted as a shim to raise the extruder. I had to compensate my lowering the z axis so low that it hit the hold downs for the glass. I ended up losing almost 3 inches on the Y axis. No good. I tested the part to see how it did at cooling. It cooled really well, but noted that I lost almost 15 deg C on the heated platform. :-/ Not wanting to find another solution for my heated platform I kept looking. Then I found http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:15899. So I tested placing the fan on the side where it would still move up and down with the extruder. The headed platform only lost 3deg C and the parts printed really well. This part completely replaces the wood one the Printrbot came with. I did this so I could use the same screws. The hardware store near my house doesn't carry 6-32x1 3/4 screws. 2 inch would hit the drive belt. I've attached an image of two gears I printed. Both at .2mm layer height. The gear on the left is with the fan on and the gear on the right is with the fan off.

Just print it out, I used .4 fill with Slic3r.  It matters how you install the part.  One direction will place the fan too close to the extruder carrier and will stop it prematurly.  I have pictures of it as I did this first.  Then I realized the part could be flipped and the carrier had the needed clearance. This is for a 40mm fan.  I got mine from some spare parts I took off the chip set of a discarded computer.

title: Chevy Colorado Front Pocket AMPS Dock

description.text:
The tiny front pocket in the dash of the '15 and up Colorado is nearly useless. Even if you shove a wallet or garage door opener in there it'll slide right out if you hit the gas at all. This 'pocket dock' for phone or tablet gives it some purpose.

To use the dock you'll want 10lb 'poster' tape - the kind that is a mm or two thick. Place a piece on the top and bottom flat parts, pinch, and insert into the dock. The hole pattern matches industry standard AMPS. Once appropriately installed it is pretty locked in. You're more likely to rip the phone from the mount than the dock from the pocket.

There are three different versions. the base version sits very close to the dock edge and is appropriate for RAM ball style docks or other longer, positionable docs. The medium-lower dock hangs below the pocket and is appropriate for most phones and likely horizontal tablets. The 'long' version is good for lower profile docks (eg: magnetic).

Notes:

Super-easy to print on its side as long as you have decent bed adhesion.

description.text:
Very simple part to mount the SN04 inductive sensor.
The differences with the original are :

  • Add a guide to easily adjust the position of the sensor.
  • Add nut shapes

You'll need 2 M3 screws and nuts.

Synet3D firmware: https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B0Jb9SruV4vGM1hDZnhnd3Q3WUU/view

  • Cura printer parameter :

=> Start gcode :

G21 ;metric values
G90 ;absolute positioning
M82 ;set extruder to absolute mode
M107 ;start with the fan off
G28 X0 Y0 ;move X/Y to min endstops
G28 Z0 ;define the 0 software position
G29 ;auto leveling on 9 points of the bed
G1 Z15.0 F{travel_speed} ;move the platform down 15mm
G0 X2 Y2 Z2
G92 E0 ;zero the extruded length
G1 F200 E25 ;extrude 3mm of feed stock
G92 E0 ;zero the extruded length again
G1 F{travel_speed}
M117 Printing...

=> Stop gcode :

;End GCode
M104 S0 ;extruder heater off
M140 S0 ;heated bed heater off (if you have it)
G91 ;relative positioning
G1 E-1 F300 ;retract the filament a bit before lifting the nozzle, to release some of the pressure
G1 Z+5.5 E-5 X-20 Y-20 F{travel_speed} ;move Z up a bit and retract filament even more
G28 X0 Y0 ;move X/Y to min endstops, so the head is out of the way
M84 ;steppers off
G90 ;absolute positioning

  • Below a summary of the offset setting steps:

    If you don't use octoprint, connect your computer with printer with your SUB cable.
    Launch pronterface software, you can download it her http://www.pronterface.com/.
    With pronterface you can control the motors and sens commands in a terminal.
    Preheat nozzle and bed (nozzle 200°C / Bed 60°C)
    In a terminal, send this command: M851 Z0
    In a terminal, send this command: M500
    In a terminal, send this command: G28 (Lanch autolevel for all axis)
    In a terminal, send this command: G1 X110 Y110 (Move the nozzle in the center of the plate).
    Place a paper below the nozzle
    With octoprint or pronterface, move down the nozzle 10mm.
    Move down the nozzle 0.1mm per 0.1mm until the paper can't move.
    Move up the nozzle of 0.1mm
    On your printer screen, note the Z level value (for exemple 1.2)
    In a terminal, send this command: M851 Z-X.XX where X.XX is the noted value.
    In a terminal, send this command: M500 (to sauve the offset in the EEPROM)

title: Nodal Ninja 3 kit to provide 6 degree detent

description.text:
A friend in the US asked for a high res image of Sydney Harbour Bridge and Opera House for blowing up to about 4ft x 8ft.
The minimum angle available on the standard Nodal Ninja 3 detents is 15 degrees which was not fine enough for my needs.
Hence this design which provides a 6 degree detent.
And here is the result: https://flic.kr/p/WYwKkf
Designed in Moment of Inspiration (Moi3D) and printed in PETG on a Prusa Original i3 Mk2 and on a Kodama Trinus. Simplify3D slicer used for the Trinus and Prusa Slic3r used for the Prusa Original i3 MK2 4 colour.
The detent plate and the pin need to be made from a 'hard' material. I think that PLA would be OK but I doubt that parts made from ABS would last very long.
The design needs hardware.
I used:
7-off 3MM x 10mm long button head cap screws
1-off 6MM x 35mm (under the head) socket head cap screw
1-off compression spring. 7mm diameter, free length 20mm, solid height 5mm. 6 full turns. Wire diameter 0.5mm.
A brief video is here: https://youtu.be/JPQH2QBTUew

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Mk2

Resolution:

variou

Infill:

20%

Notes:

The end of the pin is difficult to print well and the detail of the detents is important. I used one of the fancy features of Simplify3D on these two parts. This allowed me to print most of each part with 0.2mm layer height, and the crucial sections of each part at 0.05mm layer height. These I printed on the Kodama Trinus mostly because Simplify3D is not yet compatible with the latest 4 colour version of the Prusa Original i3 Mk2.
Other parts printed on the Prusa with 0.2mm layer height.
As already mentioned I printed all parts in PETG.
I think that PLA would work OK, in fact the screw holes sizes are for PLA and are a little small for PETG.

Important. The 6mm screw should be a tight fit in the detent plate so that the detent plate, the screw and the keeper rotate as one unit. If you can't achieve this for some reason, use the hole provided in the side of the detent plate to jam something (a bit of filament?) against the side of the 6mm screw using a 3mm screw (making the total number of 3mm x 10mm long screws 8).
All done in Moment of Inspiration.

title: Easy Access E3D V5 SINGLE fan duct holder

description.text:
The original was made by trustfm. I remixed this because I was having difficulties with the plastic ties, which have to be cut every time to service the E3D's.

This version introduces a pivot and locking mechanism, which makes both fans really accessible. Also, the original had tight parameters around the fan ducts, which made them difficult to remove.

Both fan ducts are left untouched from the originals, so they should work with my version (assuming you printed "Fan-Duck-Left_-repaired-oriented" and "Fan-Duck-Right-repaired-_oriented"). Having said that, I did repair the right side to fix the slicing errors.

For right hand version print:

E3D_V5_Right_Side_FAN_Body_PIVOT_PT1
E3D_V5_Right_Side_FAN_Body_PIVOTPT2
Fan-Duck-Right-repaired-_oriented

For Left hand version print:
E3D_V5_Left_Side_FAN_Body_PIVOT_PT1
E3D_V5_Left_Side_FAN_Body_PIVOTPT2
Fan-Duck-Left-repaired-_oriented

Recommend printing settings:

-Layer height: .2
-use 2mm Brim on both Fan Body PT's. Both parts are small and will detach from your heating bed.
-use bridges

Recommend hardware:
1x M3x30 hex bolt
1x M3x25 hex bolt
2x M3 locking nuts

Enjoy!

Print this and be done with your service issues! If you're new to E3D's, this will make your life very easy. Also, you really don't need two fans. If your layers are separating, then your filament is cooling too quickly.

title: Waterbowl for long eared dogs like my Afghan hound

description.text:
I have a (very long eared) Afghan hound and a (long) bearded Schnauzer. The first drinks often and has constantly wet ears, the 2nd has always a wet beard which she tries to dry on my trousers ....

The Idea is the present only a small and constant quantity of water on a small surface to the dog.
A first test with a floating insert in a small bucket seems to work well.
So the path to a more designed version was just a small step.

Bowl and floating insert can be cleaned easily. Not tested yet, but should be dishwasher proof.
Insert weighs around 340 grams for a volume of 0,9 liter

Dimensions :
Diameter of the bowl is 210 mm, height is 120 mm

Printing :
I printed the parts in PETg which is considered safe for food. It is strong, has some flex and has a very good layer bond (Water- and airtight!).
S3D factory files are included. Especially the one for the floating insert uses some S3D features. I gradually changed infill from 10% to 25% (bottom to top) to have a smoother toplayer.
Nozzle used (my standard) : 0,6mm.
Layer 0,48mm (but that's my choice... Don't need that detail)
Printing temperature : 270°C
Bed temperature : 70°C

Pictures of the bowl or a movie when in use will follow .

Should work also for spaniels, bearded collie ...
Water volume is around 2,5 liters

Modifications
20170728
Increased the internal diameter of the bowl a bit. Was a too tight fit for the floating insert...
New STL and Factory file for the bowl
Added a picture of the finished bowl.
Schnauzer still has a wet beard :( but not as wet as before, works very well for my Afghan Hound.

After a couple of weeks using the bowl, I'm very happy with the result.
As I printed it in black PETG and the bowl being outside the house (sunlight!) the advantages compared to open metal bowls or clear ones are :

  • no green slimy algae forming in the bowl
  • very easy to clean. Just daily passing with a brush. One sees that PETG is water repellent and remains very clean.
  • 2,5 litres of water is enough for one day for the 2 dogs.

description.text:
This is a mount for a kinect sensor. Unlike many of the others on thingiverse this one is designed to be a very secure mount, while at the same time allowing the sensor to be easily removed.

It uses sliding lugs to securely latch the kinect sensor to the mount. These mounts are tightened and held in place with 20mm M3 bolts and embedded nuts.

The mount attaches to either an Arca style tripod mount, or the 19 or 25.4mm pole mounts with a 1/4" bolt (as used in camera equipment).

The pole mounts use M5 bolts with embedded nuts.

The sensor mount also has two grooves under it, 10mm offset from the mount centre, designed to fit 30.0 x 2.0 x 1.2mm ridges as seen on the arca or pole clamps. They are there to prevent the clamp twisting on the mount. If you wish to design your own clamps, you may want to include these ridges to prevent loosening/twisting.

description.text:
The mod contains parts for https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1915956:

  • A remix of the crossbar thumbnuts that now use M4 hex-head screws in order to achieve better grip and allow assembly/disassembly.
  • Improved version of the scope windage knob and scope windage mount that now look much closer to the original part.
  • The hammer mechanism is modified to be able to fit a bolt.
  • The crossbar contains a place for an M4 hex-head bolt on the back at the middle hole.
  • Sight leaf clip that prevents sight leaf from falling out, while allowing it to move up and down.

Required:

  • 3x M4 hex-head screws with thin head (3mm), overall length 20mm;
  • 3x M4 hex-head bolts, thin head (2-3mm)
  • Gel Super-Glue

No

Notes:

Use supports for Part 32 (hammer mechanism).

Mounting the Screws

Insert the screws heads in the printed thumbscrews, make sure they are all the way in (use a vice if required) and glue them with a few drops of super-glue.

If you need to use a vice, you must first screw a bolt, because you will most likely damage the threads, and unscrewing a bolt that is already on the screw will be the best way to fix it.

Middle thumbnut consists of 3 parts, while the two side thumbnuts consist of 2 parts.

Fitting the Bolts

You can print the modified crossbar that has a place for fitting a bolt, but you can also modify your existing part by expanding the middle hole with a 6.8-7 mm drill bit but not all the way - just 3 mm in depth. Then use a vice to force a bolt in.

For the other two bolts you can just put them on the inside of the gun and wind them on the screws.

DO NOT OVER-TIGHTEN!

Refactored Scope Windage Knob & Mount

New scope knob and mount are refactored to match the original. Two screw heads are added on the top, together with 8 hairlines. The mount is redesigned from the scratch, according to the many available photos of the original scope.

Before painting, it is advisable to sand the parts. Painted using golden Revel Model Paint 321 94 and weathered using black acrylic paint.

Sight Leaf Clip

The clip prevents sight leaf from falling out, while allowing it to rotate with a reasonable amount of force.

The clip should tightly fit its place. If it's too tight, use some sand paper to sand it down. If it's too loose, you can either slightly increase its size before the print, or you can spray some paint to gain thickness. However, before mounting the leaf, first try if it fits without the sight leaf, because once mounted, it will be hard to remove.

To finalize the assembly, first mount the sight leaf, then slide the clip in. Use a flat screwdriver to force it in place.

description.text:
This is a quick release plate designed to replace the Sirui TY-C10.

I like how these plates are slim, light and still fit the arca-swiss standard - they're perfect for my old 35mm film cameras. But they are expensive too, so having one for each camera can be a considerable expense... so I designed and printed my own.

There's also a tripod screw if you're some kind of scrooge, but be aware: there's a reason these screws are made out of metal. If you print it, make sure your settings and material priorize layer adhesion over print speed; otherwise your camera will break because you were too miserly to spend 2€ on a real screw.

However it works as a proof of concept and I guess if you print it really hot in polycarbonate it could even stand some real action with lightweight cameras. I will update on that cause as soon as I've done some tests. Update: nope. It breaks quite easily, even with PC. And it breaks across the layers; so it most likely won't get any better. So just don't use a plastic screw.

PS: The photo is from a previous version of the plate. I still have to update the picture with the most recent version which has more chamfered/blended edges and deeper grooves. It's also time to replace my old print bed as the surface finish really looks horrible. Updated pic: New version made out of PC. Screw is still greentec.

Wanhao

Wanhao Duplicator i3 V2

No

100%

Notes:

Both parts are designed to be printed without support.

Plate: Print it upside down in a material which is: stiff, not too brittle, can stand some heat (think of storing it in your car or of attaching a modern mirrorless camera which can get pretty hot), has good layer adhesion. Lignine-based greentec from extrudr seems perfect for that case. But PC (maybe a bit too flexible?) or ABS (hard to print steep angles with good layer adhesion) most likely will do the job as well.

Screw: It's a rather tight fit so consider reducing the X/Y size to 95-98%. As already mentioned, make sure your printer is set to max out its layer-adhesion capabilities. Material-wise I'd choose something like PC, perhaps even PETG if you feel adventurous. However I want to emphasize that I don't recommend using a plastic screw on expensive and/or heavy cameras!
Think of adding some thin self-sticking rubber pad to prevent the camera from movement.

title: Hex ScrewDriver Stand cnc
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I got a set of hey key screwdrivers I use quite often. The small sizes are hard to distinguish as the print on the handle has rub off. The idea was to built a stand with clear labeling.

It was built from some 20 mm laminated plywood and some more of the aluminum-polyethylene-compound material (Aludibond) I used for my Leaflet Display.

The laminated plywood was a great material to engrave the size labels. If engraved to a very shallow depth of 0.4 mm so the white surface was milled away and the black laminate showed through. Aludibond can be bend perfectly if you use a specialized tool: a BOX-Router Bit.

The parts were cut with my Stepcraft desktop cnc-machine and a spiral-toothed 3 mm flute for the wood and a 2 mm single-flute end-mill to cut the compound-material. I drilled the holes for mounting the screws and for the screwdrivers itself with a drill-press. Before assembly I oiled the wood. Four round self-adhesive felt feet finalized the built and gave it a secure stand.

Visit https://www.zenziwerken.de/en/ for more interesting designs.
A first prototype did without the bottom plate. It has shown that this realization needed some improvement in terms of stability and design.
